      "subsection": "THE HESSIAN MATRIX, LOCAL MAXIMA/MINIMA, AND MULTIDIMENSIONAL TAYLOR SERIES",
      "position": 11,
      "depth": 1,
      "context_text": "In univariate calculus, the local extrema of a function occur when its slope (first derivative) is zero. The multivariate extension is that the gradient vector is zero, so the slope of the function with respect to all variables is zero. A point $ x_{e} $ where this occurs is called a stationary or equilibrium point, and corresponds to either a local maximum, minimum, saddle point, or inflection point. As with the calculus of single variables, determining which of these cases is correct depends on the second derivative. With n variables, the appropriate generalization is the Hessian matrix",
